      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T09:03:00Z",
      "webTitle":" Charlie Hunnam quit Fifty Shades 'after being refused extensive creative input'",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/oct/17/fifty-shades-charlie-hunnam-script-approval",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/2013/oct/17/fifty-shades-charlie-hunnam-script-approval",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p>The mystery of why the Sons of Anarchy star walked away from Fifty Shades appears one step closer to being solved after reports that he was keen to secure script approval</p>",
        "headline":" Charlie Hunnam quit Fifty Shades 'after being refused extensive creative input'",
        "body":"<p>Charlie Hunnam walked away from a high-profile role as kinky billionaire Christian in Sam Taylor-Johnson's upcoming Fifty Shades of Grey movie after being denied extensive script approval, <a href=\"http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/fifty-shades-charlie-hunnams-script-648778\">according to the Hollywood Reporter</a>.</p><p>Further details are now beginning to emerge about the Sons of Anarchy star's surprise last-minute departure from the much-hyped adaptation of EL James' bestselling \"mommy porn\" literary sensation at the weekend. Hunnam officially cited a lack of time to prepare for the role of Christian Grey due to his busy TV schedule, and there have also been suggestions he got \"cold feet\" due to overwhelming attention from the 70 million or so fans who have bought James' book or its two sequels. Now it's being reported (in the latest edition of the US trade bible's print issue) that the British actor quit after his demands for creative input eventually caused a rift with producers.</p><p>\"Hunnam, who also is a writer (he penned the gothic horror screenplay Vlad for Brad Pitt's Plan B and Summit Entertainment), is said to have submitted his own very detailed script notes on Kelly Marcel's adaptation of the runaway best-seller,\" according to the Hollywood Reporter's article. \"The notes were well received, according to sources, but that only led to Hunnam seeking further script approval, which was denied.</p><p>\"According to another source, Hunnam, who was to be paid about $125,000 for the film, began butting heads with the creative team, including Taylor-Johnson. The conflict reached a fever pitch in early October, though everyone involved thought the issues had been resolved. </p><p>\"But the discord spiked again [on] October 11. Hunnam's team at CAA and Brillstein Entertainment Partners strongly advised him to stay on the project for fear that his exit would burn a bridge with one of the major studios. That same day, Universal hired writer Patrick Marber - no stranger to taboo sex themes with his Oscar-nominated screenplay Notes on a Scandal - to do a polish and bolster the characters. But by then, Hunnam, whose heart it seems never was in the project, had decided to decamp.\"</p><p>Alexander Skarsgard of the supernatural-themed HBO television series True Blood and Jamie Dornan of Belfast-set BBC drama The Fall were reported earlier this week to be the new frontrunners to replace Hunnam. Universal may also return to previous candidates for the role of Christian, who include Theo James, Christian Cooke and Garrett Hedlund. Dakota Johnson, best known for small roles in the Oscar-winning The Social Network and comedy The Five Year Engagement, remains in the lead female role of Anastasia Steele.</p><p>In James' novels, business magnate Christian recruits blushing virgin Anastasia to be his well-remunerated sex-slave. Fifty Shades of Grey is expected to be the first in a trilogy based on the British author's triptych of books, which also include Fifty Shades Darker and Fifty Shades Freed.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/oct/15/fifty-shades-of-grey-movie-crisis-new-lead-actor\">• Alexander Skarsgard and Jamie Dornan in running to take over lead</a></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420232935|2013-10-17T16:29:07Z|12426f87bf430e911b7e3a3127c9f03639e65c8e -->",
